## Severity
Major
## Dimension
error-handling
## Location
src/main.rs:255-303 (cmd_tui), 791-841 (resolve_chat_auth)
## Violation
cmd_tui prints user-facing errors to stderr but always returns Ok(()) — exit code 0. This breaks `set -e` shell wrappers and any orchestration that branches on exit status.

```rust
async fn cmd_tui(model_override: Option<String>) -> anyhow::Result<()> {
    let mut config = match config::load_config() {
        Ok(c) => c,
        Err(e) => {
            ...
            eprintln!("Failed to parse configuration: {e}");
            ...
            return Ok(());  // Exit 0 despite error
        }
    };
    ...
    let Some(provider) = config.active_provider() else {
        eprintln!("No provider configured for target '{}'", config.proxy.target);
        return Ok(());  // Exit 0
    };
    let Some(ChatAuth { ... }) = resolve_chat_auth(...).await? else {
        return Ok(());  // Exit 0 — resolve_chat_auth printed the error
    };
```

cmd_chat has the same pattern in resolve_chat_auth: returns Ok(None) for "we already printed an error" and Err(_) only for "unexpected I/O", which the caller then maps with `else { return Ok(()) }`. The error-vs-non-error distinction is collapsed at the exit boundary, defeating the perimeter-defense rule.

## Mandated refactor
Return anyhow::Error with descriptive messages and let `?` propagate to main(). main() can map specific error categories to specific exit codes via std::process::ExitCode if user-friendly messaging is the concern (anyhow's `Display` already provides clean output). The eprintln messages can stay for human readability while the exit code reflects actual failure.

